article.headline: N. Dakota St. 60, Furman 58
article.story: FARGO, N.D. (AP) -- North Dakota State rallied from a nine-point halftime deficit to beat Furman 60-58 Wednesday in men's basketball. The Bison (2-2) won it at the free throw line despite making just six of 14 attempts in the second half. NDSU's last field goal was a 3-pointer by Brett Winkelman that tied it at 56-56 with 3:31 to play. Ben Woodside's free throw with 1:27 broke a 58-58 tie. Mike Nelson added a free throw with 8 seconds to play for the Bison, who trailed 33-24 at the break. Furman missed two shots as time ran out. The Paladins were just 9-for-29 in the second half after shooting 33 percent in the first half. Moussa Diagne a career-high 27 points for Furman (3-2). Eric Webb added 11 points. NDSU shot 33 percent in the first half and 54 percent after the break. Andre Smith had 15 of his career-high 24 points and nine of his 11 rebounds for the Bison after half. Winkelman scored 13 points and Nelson 12 for NDSU. Nelson sparked a 13-5 second-half run with a 3-pointer that cut the Bison deficit to 37-35 with 14:16 remaining. Despite its struggles offensively, Furman led from the opening shot until Lucas Moorman's jumper with 4:44 to play gave NDSU its first lead at 53-52. There were two ties and three lead changes down the stretch. Moorman had 13 rebounds to help the Bison to a 42-34 advantage on the boards.
